# Phase B canary (PB0 → PB1 → PB2 → M20i.1 → PB3 → PB4 layers).
#
# Purpose: anchor the reactive validation milestone. Per the
# GPT-5.5 Phase B checkpoint, this file is NOT a library — it's
# the canary that proves each Phase B substrate piece composes
# end-to-end (REACTIVITY-DESIGN.md §Phase B).
#
# The canary has grown alongside each substrate milestone:
#
#   PB0    baseline: Cell + stack-local closure        ✅ shipped
#   M20h   owned/escaping closure values               ✅ shipped
#   PB1    single retained Effect (folded M20h(5/5))   ✅ shipped
#   M20i   resource-aware Vec(T)                       ✅ shipped
#   PB2    Signal: single-subscriber notification      ✅ shipped
#   M20i.1 resource-Vec iteration `for cb in ?subs`    ✅ shipped
#   PB3    multi-subscriber Signal (R2 reentrancy)     ✅ shipped
#   PB4    reentrant set queues + coalesces            ✅ shipped
#          (backward-compat; not visible in canary)
#
# Each substrate gap exposed by the canary gets fixed on main,
# not in the library. Per the design doc: "the library is the
# canary; fix the language, not the library."
#
# PB4 note: the R2 reentrant-set relaxation is a backward-
# compatible change — same-Signal `set` from a subscriber body
# now queues (coalescing to most-recent value) instead of
# panicking. The canary doesn't exercise this case directly
# because a terminating reentrant-set demo requires conditional
# logic in the closure body (not available in V1 inline-body
# grammar). The R2 relaxation is documented in SPEC §Signal +
# verified by non-regression of the existing canary output.

sub main()
  # Substrate check #1: M20f Cell(T) interior mutability through
  # a shared *T handle. The Reactor-less precursor to Cell.set
  # that drives push-invalidation in the full library.
  count: *Cell(Int) = *Cell(value: 0)
  count.set(1)
  print(count.get())                # 1

  # Substrate check #2: M20g stack-local closure capturing a
  # shared handle by clone. Confirms the closure body can read
  # through the captured Rc. The retained-Effect case (M20h)
  # generalizes this to closures that outlive their defining
  # scope.
  bump = |+count|
    count.set(count.get() + 1)
  bump()
  bump()
  print(count.get())                # 3

  # PB1 (M20h shipped): retained escaping closure. The reactive
  # library needs a closure value that can be stored in an Effect
  # (or Reactor subscriber list) and invoked after the defining
  # scope exits. M20g closures were strictly non-escaping; M20h
  # introduced `*Closure(|...| body)` — a heap-owned closure
  # with type-erased ABI (rig.Closure0 vtable + per-literal env
  # struct) and last-strong-drop capture cleanup via __rig_drop.
  #
  # The minimal Effect-shaped invocation: build a closure that
  # captures the Cell, retain it past the defining scope, and
  # invoke it explicitly. PB2 will add Cell → Effect notification
  # (Reactor.flush); for now PB1 demonstrates the substrate.
  eff: *Closure() = *Closure(|+count| count.set(count.get() + 10))
  eff()
  print(count.get())                # 13

  # PB2 (Signal primitive shipped): single-subscriber Cell →
  # Effect notification. The Signal(T) builtin combines a
  # Cell-like value slot with an OPTIONAL retained closure
  # subscriber. On `signal.set(v)`, the value updates AND the
  # subscriber (if any) is invoked synchronously. This is the
  # minimum viable reactive primitive — proves "retained
  # subscriber observes state change" without committing to
  # multi-subscriber semantics or batching/topology (those
  # land in PB3 after resource-Vec iteration is designed).
  #
  # Per GPT-5.5's PB2 design: single subscriber is enough to
  # validate the load-bearing claim. Don't pre-bake
  # multi-subscriber until the actual gap (Vec iteration)
  # is designed under real use pressure.
  sig: *Signal(Int) = *Signal(value: 0)
  log: *Closure() = *Closure(|+sig| print(sig.get()))
  sig.subscribe(+log)
  sig.set(7)                        # 7  (set triggers log)
  sig.set(99)                       # 99 (same)

  # M20i.1 (resource-Vec iteration): `for cb in ?subs` walks a
  # `Vec(*Closure())` and invokes each retained subscriber via a
  # borrowed view of the slot. This is the substrate primitive
  # PB3's multi-subscriber Signal will use internally — the
  # canary block below proves the iteration shape composes with
  # the M20h escaping-closure + M20i Vec drop-cascade
  # discipline. Per GPT-5.5's M20i.1 design pass:
  #   - `?subs` is mandatory for resource-element Vec iteration
  #     (sema rejects bare-source iteration with a tailored
  #     diagnostic pointing at `?vec`).
  #   - The loop binding `cb` is a read borrow of the Vec slot;
  #     it may be called (`cb()`) but NOT cloned/moved/dropped
  #     (ownership rejects those with a tailored diagnostic).
  #   - The loop body is forbidden from write-borrowing `subs`
  #     (e.g., `(!subs).push(...)`) by the standard borrow-
  #     conflict rule — the loop installs a scope-bound read
  #     borrow on the source.
  notes: *Cell(Int) = *Cell(value: 0)
  one:   *Closure() = *Closure(|+notes| notes.set(notes.get() + 1))
  ten:   *Closure() = *Closure(|+notes| notes.set(notes.get() + 10))
  cent:  *Closure() = *Closure(|+notes| notes.set(notes.get() + 100))
  subs: Vec(*Closure()) = Vec()
  (!subs).push(+one)
  (!subs).push(+ten)
  (!subs).push(+cent)
  for cb in ?subs
    cb()
  print(notes.get())                # 111 (1 + 10 + 100)

  # PB3 (multi-subscriber Signal): now generalize Signal from
  # PB2's single-slot subscriber to a `Vec(*Closure())` of
  # retained subscribers. The Rig surface is unchanged
  # (`sig.subscribe(+cb)`), but the runtime now appends rather
  # than replaces, and `signal.set(v)` walks every subscriber
  # synchronously in subscription order. Reentrancy is strict:
  # calling `set` or `subscribe` during an active notification
  # panics in V1 (the "notifying" flag is the runtime guard).
  # PB4 may relax this to queue/snapshot semantics if the canary
  # exposes a real use case.
  #
  # The two notification primitives are now both available:
  #   - User-written external `for cb in ?subs` (above) — for
  #     code that wants explicit control of the walk.
  #   - Internal `signal.set(v)` (below) — Signal's builtin
  #     synchronous notify-all. Substrate-wise the two are
  #     equivalent; the Signal builtin packages "value cell +
  #     subscriber list + notify-on-set" for ergonomics.
  tally: *Cell(Int) = *Cell(value: 0)
  add_a: *Closure() = *Closure(|+tally| tally.set(tally.get() + 1))
  add_b: *Closure() = *Closure(|+tally| tally.set(tally.get() + 10))
  add_c: *Closure() = *Closure(|+tally| tally.set(tally.get() + 100))
  multi: *Signal(Int) = *Signal(value: 0)
  multi.subscribe(+add_a)
  multi.subscribe(+add_b)
  multi.subscribe(+add_c)
  multi.set(42)                     # invokes all three: tally 0 → 111
  print(tally.get())                # 111

  # PB4 shipped a minimal R2 relaxation: same-Signal reentrant
  # `set` from inside a subscriber body now queues (coalesce-
  # to-latest) instead of panicking. Reentrant `subscribe`
  # still panics (list-mutation during iteration is subtler
  # and locking the policy would force a mini-Reactor design).
  #
  # The full reactive library (Reactor / Memo / Effect
  # lifecycle / cross-Signal batching / dependency-graph
  # topology) is explicitly USERLAND work per GPT-5.5
  # entry 33 — Rig holds the same position as Rust and Zig:
  # substrate in the language, reactive library in userland.
  # Signal stays the canary primitive; further reactivity
  # builds OUTSIDE the language, once Cell-non-Copy or
  # equivalent substrate lands.
